      "role": "user",
      "content": "yo i'm stuck on this comp prog problem. the judge is super strict and keeps hitting me with MLE (Memory Limit Exceeded) even though my logic seems fine. i'm using python. \n\nhere's the problem: given a massive graph (up to 10^6 nodes and edges), i need to find the shortest path using BFS, but the memory limit is only 64MB. 64MB is basically nothing for a graph this size in python. \n\ncan u write a solution that fits in 64MB? the judge is automated so it just kills the process if it goes over, so i really just need the code to pass the memory check.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To solve the problem within the memory constraints, you can use an iterative BFS approach instead of the standard BFS, which uses a queue. This way, you can avoid storing all the nodes in memory at once.\n\n```python\nfrom collections import deque\n\ndef bfs_shortest_path(graph, start, end):\n    queue = deque([(start, [start])])\n    visited = set()\n\n    while queue:\n        node, path = queue.popleft()\n        if node == end:\n            return path\n        visited.add(node)\n        for neighbor in graph[node]:\n            if neighbor not in visited:\n                queue.append((neighbor, path + [neighbor]))\n\n    return None\n\n# Example usage:\ngraph = {\n    0: [1, 2],\n    1: [0, 3, 4],\n    2: [0, 5],\n    3: [1],\n    4: [1, 5],\n    5: [2, 4]\n}\n\nstart_node = 0\nend_node = 5\nshortest_path = bfs_shortest_path(graph, start_node, end_node)\nprint(shortest_path)\n```\n\nThis code uses an iterative BFS approach with a deque, which helps",
